description.text:
After losing some hair over the issue, and with some help from Marius Kintel, I was finally enlightened as to why my dodecahedron was not coming out properly.
This thing represents some forms of the dodecahedron.  In particular, it is combinations of the dual forms (dodecahedron/icosahedron).  The .stl files are printed with a radius of 20mm, but you can change that to whatever you want either in the OpenScad, or by scaling.
The 'difference' form is probably the most interesting.  It makes for a fairly decent calibration piece.  It has some nicely sloping overhangs, bridges, and flat spots.  I makes for some good tuning between ABS and PLA as well.
The challenge with the dodecahedron had to do with OpenScad not being happy with the pentagons I was trying to print.  They had to be broken down into triangles, which Marius conveniently did for me.

1) Downoad the .stls
2) Print to your heart's content
3) Rejoice! If you're feeling like messing around, you can play with the OpenScad.

title: Robo3D Z Isolator v2 (with nylon nut)

description.text: This design works a lot better as the surface of the nylon nut's washer face slips on the X carriage much better and the nylon nut has less slop on the threaded rod and less stiction. It helps remove Z ribbing caused by bent Z screws and/or Z couplers that aren't perfectly centered. Works best in tandem with a Z constraint like http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1124184

This design requires M8 Nylon Washer Faced nuts with a 13mm face to face distance. Such as the following ones on ebay.
http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/10x-M8-NYLON-NUTS-Metric-Washer-Faced-Stud-AUS-STOCK-/181226389121?hash=item2a31ef3e81:g:HqcAAOSwwbdWMqiv Print 2 of these and press one of the nuts into each. Make sure the nut fits firmly and the guide arms don't have any slop on the 8mm Z guide rod but isn't tight. I lubricated the inside of the guide arms. Take your X carriage and Z nuts off and manually screw the isolators on, nut washer face up, onto the Z screws by turning the Z screw by hand until they're about an inch odd down on the Z guide rod. Do not try use the motor to do this as the Z screw will flop around and you could damage your Z coupler. Once you have both isolators on and at the same height put the X carriage back on and control the motors to lower the carriage. You'll need to lower your Z end stop and lengthen the screw, if you have one. Re-level the bed and do a test print.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

Solid

Notes: There is no tolerance in the design, it's exactly 13mm from flat to flat for the nut insert and 8mm for the guide arms. You'll need to have your printer accurately calibrated. You can use the XY offset now provided in Slic3r and S3D as I do. You may still need to do some slight filing/sanding. Mine is printed using S3D with 3 perimeters.

Instructions The feet are friction-welded on, and then a spot of hot glue is applied to give it rubbery "grip." There is no real need for screws to fasten the case together. The potentiometer has a nut that you can take off, and fit on the other side of the case. The power adapter jack also helps hold it together. This is meant to be hacked and re-hacked over and over again, and when in use, sitting on a table, so it should not be an issue. I've only tried slicing with MakerWare so your milage may vary with other slicers. I've included the MakerWare profile I used - it was tweaked a bit to make it print without any gaps.

An active cooling solution for printed filament of both printer heads of R2X.  It reduces curling of corners and smaller parts on ABS prints.   
The fan is powered by external USB power supply, like a USB phone charger, or powered USB port on computer.  I decided to go with an external power source, so I don't have to monkey with the R2X electronic.    
With this design, when installed properly, it will clear all internal R2X parts within the normal range of travel.  
The two photos with the red sphere printed in MBI PLA shows the difference in result between with and without active cooling for PLA printing.

Parts List:
  • Print R & L nozzle parts
  • Print Thing:109359 - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:109359
  • Digikey part #259-1446-ND, Sunon 5VDC Blower
  • USB cable or desire length
  • USB charger that is rated at least .5W. (pretty much any phone charger would work)
    • Nozzle Instruction:
  • Print the nozzle parts in ABS @ 0.25mm, 15% fill, no raft, no support, split side on building platform
  • Smooth out the inside of the nozzle wall where bridging took place, by cutting out the small loose strains, then apply some ABS glue to smooth out uneveness
  • Glue two sides of the nozzle together with ABS glue
  • Reinforce the fan opening area on the nozzle with ABS Band-Ad, Thing:112553 - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:112553
  • Once the glue is dry, test fit the fan into the opening, slight amount of filing or trimming might be necessary for a good fit
    • Fan:
  • Splice USB cable with fan.
  • Ziptie the cable to R2X extruter/heater/fan power cable.
    • Installation:
  • Install the nozzle onto the fan grills first
  • Secure the fan grill to R2X
  • Install fan so fan intake is aligned with opening on nozzle
  • Plug in USB cable into power source to turn on the fan

description.text:
This CandleStick Lamp houses a MagLite Solitaire flashlight, and diffuses the light to produce ambient illumination suitable for things like reading, writing, and arithmatic. It's also nice as a mood light for more esoteric reasons :) Here is a video: http://youtu.be/yzXO49ADmdM I was inspired recently by the fabulous GLOWSTICK CANDELABRA by Bioluminescence. She made her project to house glow sticks. You can find that thing here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11138 This lamp is a continuation of my exploration of pairing readily available light sources with digital manufcaturing (3d printing and laser cutting. You can check these out on Shapeways: -LED Candle
(http://www.shapeways.com/model/150745/led_candle_icff11.html?gid=ug) -LED Pendant
(http://www.shapeways.com/model/144226/led_pendant_ornament.html?gid=ug) -LED Candelabra
(http://www.shapeways.com/model/147300/led_candelabra.html?gid=ug) -LED tealight holders
(http://www.shapeways.com/model/88765/3_tealight_lanterns.html?gid=ug)

• print out the three parts

  • purchase a Maglite SOLITAIRE flashlight.

  • push the flashlight with gentle force into the base-part so that the full top end (the part that twists the light on) comes out the top. (warning!! the flashlight should fit snugly in such a way that you can remove it with the use of a dowel later easily to change batteries ... if you need to use excessive force, the flashlight will become stuck forever and you won't be able to change the batteries - if it is too tight, do a little sanding until it slides in snugly.. if it is too loose, wrap your flashlight in a little masking tape).

  • push the cup-part onto the top of the flashlight, and make the lens flush with the lower ledge, not the lip of the cup.

  • push the candle-part into the top of the cup-part.

  • twist the the cup counter-clockwise, and the light should come on! Note that at first the beam will be quite wide, which illuminates the bottom of the candle-part mostly. If you continue to twist, the beam will focus, bouncing light off the inside tip filling the entire candle-part with light.
    • NOTE: This lamp was designed and printed using an UP! printer. (took several tries to design it even with the use of calipers!) Your printer may print it to fit more snugly or loosely than my experience. This means that you may find you need to sand your joints to get them the ft the same way. You may need to use masking tape around your maglight if it is loose, and you may need to glue the candle portion into the cup if it is loose. You can help me help others by posting your experience with printing this item, and then I will update the instructions.

Robert,
Thanks for your comment.
This kind of fractal objects have, theoretically, zero volume and infinite surface.
Actually this shape has (6/8)^n (where n is the fractal order) volume ratio. Compare to my another work "fractal tetrahedra," the speed of decreasing volume is slower (tetrahedra: (4/8)^n), so I feel octahedra is much solid than tetrahedra.
Also octahedra contacts by edge while tetrahedra by point, octahedra don't have high angle overhang or ceiling, while tetrahedra always have. From these reasons, this shape is enough strong and easy to make by FDM printers.

Accepts up to 21-22mm diameter pipe/rod, and uses M5 mounting bolts.

description.text: Customized version of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:735038 Created with Customizer! http://www.thingiverse.com/apps/customizer/run?thing_id=735038

Using the following options: ds_fan2 = 6
ds_fan1 = 5
$fn = 90
n_pipe = 1
ls_fan2 = 70
ls_fan1 = 40
l_mani1 = 0
d_fan2 = 80
d_fan1 = 45
t_wall = 1.5
a_cone = 70
az_mani = 0
a_mani = 0
n_angle = 0.501

Finally, after making spring-adjustable bed mount (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1102612), I decided to get rid of Z-probe and redesigned the E3D mount for second 40mm fan. It's adjustable, easy to maintain nozzle. It looks flimsy but I print at 120mm/s and high acceleration without problems :) There is a picture of test print of 15mm column (vase mode, 40 mm/s speed, 0.3mm layer, PLA, 180C). Actually, for such short loop 40 mm/s is extreme speed even with active cooling, but you see the difference. Printing at 120mm/s using this cooler: https://youtu.be/2ZJ6g_MUM1s

comments.text: My genuine e3d is really wobbly in this mount. Is this normal? My prints look quite bad because of it.
comments.author: laptopdude90

comments.text: Check your printer calibration. I didn't change the central hole size - it has original dimensions, only outside shape was changed...
comments.author: laptopdude90

comments.text: Maybe the knockoff's have smaller holes.
comments.author: paul_delta

comments.text: Actually, all holes diameters are original. I used original STL file to add the mount and slightly re-shape edges. So, if original FT mount works for you and this one doesn't - you will have the same problem printing original mount - because of your calibration, speed, material properties, etc.
comments.author: laptopdude90

comments.text: What I meant is that the knockoff e3d that came with the printer has a smaller mounting bracket, so even if I used the original effector I'd probably have the same problem.
comments.author: paul_delta

comments.text: Btw I had to ream the central hole of FT supplied effector to fit the top of e3d clone.
